Business Context

Twitter is a social platform that has more than 300 million monthly active users. The platform is especially popular in the U.S. and has a great impact on the culture of this country. Hence, it is a good source for the companies to learn more about existing and potential customers. On Twitter, people use hashtags to identify their keywords. Thus, by getting tweets including a specific hashtag and perform different NLP and ML techniques, the brands can learn how customers are reacting about their products. In this project, assume that we are Apples marketing team, we would like to know what people are thinking about iPhone12, especially after the event in April in which the company introduced the new color for iPhone12.

Problem Description

The primary objective of our project is to pick a twitter hashtag #iPhone12, extract data pertaining to it, preprocess, and carry out sentiment analysis on the processed tweets.

Product based hashtags are powerful, as they can showcase what peoples opinions and intentions are and what is happening right now. If you are an expert on smart phones, or if you are in the business of providing smart phones, this opens an opportunity make better marketing and business decisions.

Upon classification of tweets to the prevailing sentiment, we will use H2O AutoML to get the best model to predict which Twitter users tend to tweet positively about #iphone12.It can help Apple identify potential partner influencers for their new iPhone12 Purple and for their next products also.

NLP Procedure Summary - iPhone12

The following steps will be performed: - Lower all characters - Remove the URLs, special characters, hashtags, numbers, rt, at, ismth, ag, prepositions, blank spaces at the beginning and the end, tags, and words that do not contribute to this project including apple, iphone - Turn text into tokens - Remove stopwords - Data Visualizations - Sentiment Analysis - Word Pair Association - Document-Term Matrix

# lower characters and remove unwanted characters
df = df %>%
  mutate(text = tolower(text),
         text = str_replace_all(text, "http.*", " "),
         text = str_replace_all(text, "https.*", " "),
         text = str_replace_all(text, "https", " "),
         text = str_replace_all(text,"\\<u[^\\>]*\\>"," "),
         text = str_replace_all(text, "\\<u[^\\>]*\\>"," "),
         text = str_replace_all(text, "apple", " "),
         text = str_replace_all(text, "iphone", " "),
         text = str_replace_all(text, "#[A-Za-z0-9]+", " "),
         text = str_replace_all(text, "#\\n", " "),
         text = str_replace_all(text,"[^[:graph:]]", " "),
         text = str_replace_all(text,"ag", " "),
         text = str_replace_all(text,"ismth", " "),
         text = gsub("&amp", " ",text),
         text = tolower(text),
         text = gsub("rt", " ", text),
         text = gsub("(RT|via)((?:\\b\\W*@\\w+)+)", " ",text),
         text = gsub("@\\w+", " ", text),
         text = gsub("[[:punct:]]", " ", text),
         text = gsub("[[:digit:]]", " ", text),
         text = gsub("@[a-z,A-Z]*"," ",text),
         text = gsub("[^\x01-\x7F]", "", text),
         text = gsub("[ |\t]{2,}", " ", text),
         text = gsub("[\r\n]", "", text),
         text = gsub("\\W*\\b\\w\\b\\W*", " ", text),
         text = removeWords(text,c(preposition)),
         text = gsub("^ ", "", text),
         text = gsub(" $", "", text))

# turn text into tokens
tokens <- df %>%
  unnest_tokens(output = word, input = text)

# remove stopwords
sw = get_stopwords()
cleaned_tokens <- tokens %>%
  filter(!word %in% sw$word)

For analysis, we are using 5 emotions: anger, joy , negative, positive and sadness.

People are positive about Protection. It can be inferred that Ceramic Shield front in iPhone12 makes people love the phone. Bath is also laid under positive. We can infer that Water Resistant is peoples favorite feature too.

Word Pair Association

#pairwise count
text_df <- df %>%
  unnest_tokens(input=text, word, to_lower=FALSE, drop=FALSE) %>%
  filter(!word %in% stop_words$word) %>%
  ungroup()

word_pairs <- text_df %>%
  group_by(word) %>%
  filter(n() > 5) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  pairwise_count(item=word, text, sort = TRUE, upper = FALSE) %>%
  filter(n > 10)

word_pairs %>%
  top_n(n=250) %>%
  graph_from_data_frame() %>%
  ggraph(layout = "fr") +
  geom_edge_link(aes(edge_alpha = n, edge_width = n), edge_colour = "cyan4") +
  geom_node_point(size = 2) +
  geom_node_text(aes(label = name), vjust = 1, hjust = 1) +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 3), title = element_text(size=9)) +
  ggtitle("#iPhone12 tweets Pairwise Count Graph")

Plot by Word Pairwise Count gives us the number of times word X and Y appear together within a group. Here, we can observe the strong connection between iPhone - purple due to the recent purple color iPhone launch. Similarly we can observe higher counts of iPhone and iPad and the recent event. Interestingly, Apple also introduced new iMac and and Apple TV. But the relationship between the event and those products are not as strong as the relationship between the event - iPad - Purple.

#pairwise correlation
word_corrs <- text_df %>%
  group_by(word) %>%
  filter(n() > 50) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  pairwise_cor(item=word, text, sort = TRUE) %>%
  filter(correlation > 0.01)

word_corrs %>%
  top_n(n=250) %>%
  graph_from_data_frame() %>%
  ggraph(layout = "fr") +
  geom_edge_link(aes(edge_alpha = correlation, edge_width = correlation), edge_colour = "cyan4") +
  geom_node_point(size = 2) +
  geom_node_text(aes(label = name), vjust = 1, hjust = 1) +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 3), title = element_text(size=9)) +
  ggtitle("#iPhone12 tweets Pairwise Correlation Graph")

Plot by Word Pairwise Correlation calculates how much more likely it is that either both word X and Y appear, or neither do, than that one appears without the other.

Words with higher phi are words more likely to appear togther than seperately.

From this, we can see a correlation between bluetooth - watch - airpods, other Apples devices and Amazon. So, Amazon seems to be where people tend to shop for Apples products.

Document-Term Matrix

clean_tweets<- df$text

#Corpus Creation

tweets_source<-VectorSource(clean_tweets)

# Creating vector source from the headlines of the dataset
tweets_corpus<-VCorpus(tweets_source)

clean_corpus <- function(corpus){
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removePunctuation)
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removeNumbers)
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removeWords,stopwords("en"))
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, content_transformer(tolower))
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus,stripWhitespace)
  return(corpus)
}

tweets_clean_corpus<-clean_corpus(tweets_corpus)

#Creating a Document - Term Matrix

tweets_dtm<-DocumentTermMatrix(tweets_clean_corpus)

#convert documenttermmatrix to matrix
tweets_m<-as.matrix(tweets_dtm[1:2000,])

#Sort the term frequency and look at the top 20 most frequently occuring words
term_freq<-colSums(tweets_m)

term_freq<-sort(term_freq,decreasing=TRUE)

term_freq[1:10]
##  purple     pre   order    mini  promax  amazon     ios     now airpods     new

ML Procedure Summary

Upon classification of tweets to the prevailing sentiment, we will use H2O AutoML to get the best model to predict which Twitter users tend to tweet positively about #iphone12.It can help Apple identify potential partner influencers for their new iPhone12 Purple and for their next products also based on screenName, favoriteCount, favorited, and retweetCount. The running time is 20 minutes.

#set bing as factor
tweet$bing <- as.factor(tweet$bing)
#remove NA values
tweet = filter(tweet, bing != "NA")
df1 <- tweet %>%
  group_by(screenName)  %>%
  select(screenName,bing, favoriteCount, favorited, retweetCount)
  


# split into train and test dataframe
smp_size <- floor(0.75 * nrow(df1))
set.seed(123)
train_ind <- sample(seq_len(nrow(df1)), size = smp_size)

train <- df1[train_ind, ]
test <- df1[-train_ind, ]

# Training data: Separate into x and y tibbles
x_train_tbl <- train %>% select(-bing)
y_train_tbl <- train %>% select(bing)
# Testing data
x_test_tbl <- test

#further data inspection
library(skimr)
x_train_tbl_skim = partition(skim(x_train_tbl))
names(x_train_tbl_skim)
## [1] "logical" "numeric"
x_train_tbl_skim$numeric %>% tibble()

library(recipes)
rec_obj <- recipe(~ ., data = x_train_tbl) %>%
  step_string2factor(string_2_factor_names) %>%
  step_meanimpute(all_numeric()) %>% # missing values in numeric columns
  step_modeimpute(all_nominal()) %>% # missing values in factor columns
  prep(training = x_train_tbl)
